NG}}\n| goals1 = Vargas {{goal|3}} <br> Hern\u00e1ndez {{goal|7}} <br> Stockey {{goal|50|o.g.}}\n| goals2 = Tovar {{goal|14}} <br> Davies {{goal|23}}\n| attendance = 3000\n| referee = Sicco ([[Italian Football Federation|Italy]])\n| stadium = [[Stadio Olimpico Grande Torino|Stadio Comunale]], [[Torino]]\n| nobars=1\n}}\n\n===Final===\n{{footballbox\n| date = 15 July 1970\n| team1 = {{fbw-rt|DEN}}\n| score = 2\u20130\n| team2 = {{fbw|ITA}}\n| goals1 = E. Hansen {{goal|18}} <br> Se\u0161ikov\u00e1 {{goal|68}}\n| stadium = [[Stadio Olimpico Grande Torino|Stadio Comunale]], [[Torino]]\n| attendance = 40,000\n| referee = Cosentina ([[Italian Football Federation|Italy]])\n| nobars=1\n}}\n\n==Later tournaments==\nThe tournament was followed by the [[1971 Women's World Cup]], and \"the series of [[Mundialito (women)|Mundialito tournaments]] throughout the 1980s in Italy, and [[1988 FIFA Women's Invitation Tournament|Fifa's Women's Invitation Tournament in China in 1988]]\" before the [[1991 FIFA Women's World Cup|first official Women's World Cup in China in 1991]].<ref name = \"Guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2015/jun/04/womens-world-cup-unofficial-record-breaking|title=Women\u2019s World Cup: from unofficial tournaments to record-breaking event|date=4 June 2015|accessdate=10 December 2018|author=[[Anna Kessel]]|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |last1=Barboni |first1=Luca |last2=Cecchi |first2=Gabriele |year=1999 |title=Annuario del calcio femminile 1999-2000 | publisher=Mariposa Editrice S.r.l. |location=Fornacette (Pisa, Italy)|pages=230-231|language=Italian |ref=Barboni-Cecchi}}\n\n{{FIFA Women's World Cup}}\n\n[[Category:1970 in association football]]\n[[Category:World championships in association football]]\n", "text_old": "The '''1970 Women's World Cup''' (Italian: '''Coppa del Mondo'''; sponsored name '''Martini Rosso Cup''') was a non-FIFA-sanctioned [[association football]] tournament for women which took place in Italy in July 1970. It was won by Denmark, represented by [[Boldklubben Femina]].\n\n==The tournament==\nSeven teams appeared in the tournament: England, West Germany, Denmark, Mexico, Italy, Austria and Switzerland.<ref name = \"RSSSF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesm/mondo-women70.html|title=Coppa del Mondo (Women) 1970|accessdate=10 December 2018|publisher=RSSSF}}</ref> An eighth team, Czechoslovakia, withdrew.<ref name = \"RSSSF\"/> The crowds for the tournament were \"30,000-strong\".<ref name = \"BBC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-46149887|title=Mexico 1971: When women's football hit the big time|date=7 December 2018|accessdate=10 December 2018|author=Bill Wilson|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> Denmark won the tournament after beating Italy 2\u20130 in the final.<ref name = \"RSSSF\"/>\n\n===Bracket===\n{{Round8|3rdplace=yes\n<!--Date-Place/Team 1/Score 1/Team 2/Score 2-->\n<!--quarter finals-->\n| 6 July \u2014 [[Genova]] | '''{{fbw|ENG}}''' | '''5''' | {{fbw|FRG}}  | 1\n| 9 July \u2014 [[Bologna]] | '''{{fbw|DEN}}''' | '''6''' | {{fbw|FRG}} | 1\n| 6 July \u2014 [[Bari]] | '''{{fbw|MEX}}''' | '''9''' | {{fbw|AUT}} | 0\n| 9 July \u2014 [[Salerno]] | '''{{fbw|ITA}}''' | '''2''' | {{fbw|SWI}} | 1\n<!--semi finals-->\n| 10 July \u2014 [[Milan]] | {{fbw|ENG}} | 0 | '''{{fbw|DEN}}''' | '''2'''\n| 11 July \u2014 [[Napoli]] | {{fbw|MEX}} | 1 | '''{{fbw|ITA}}''' | '''2'''\n<!--final-->\n| 13 July \u2014 [[Torino]] | '''{{fbw|DEN}}''' | '''2''' | {{fbw|ITA}} | 0\n<!--third place-->\n| 15 July \u2014 [[Torino]] | '''{{fbw|MEX}}''' | '''3''' | {{fbw|ENG}} | 2\n}}\n\n===Quarter-finals===\n{{footballbox\n| date = 6 July 1970\n| team1 = {{fbw-rt|ENG}}\n| goals1 = Briggs {{goal|1||9}} <br> Stockley {{goal|25|pen}} <br> Cross {{goal|36}} <br> [[Sue Lopez|Lopez]] {{goal|61}}   \n| score = 5\u20131\n| team2 = {{fbw|FRG}}\n| goals2 = Schmitz {{goal|49}}\n| stadium = [[Stadio Luigi Ferraris]], [[Genova]